2:["$","$L8",null,{"book":{"title":"Blood-Sweating Horses","author":"Li Yu","year":"1995","chapters":[{"id":"chapter-1","title":"O, the New Continent of Central Asia","poems":[{"id":"poem-1-1","title":"That Glorious Arrow Must Still Be in Flight / Cast toward the Distant West","lines":["The blood-red setting sun is about to die","The dark-gold curtain of night about to fall","Zhang Qian drives his herded flock homeward","A desolate pastoral song blends with the mournful reed-pipe","Piercing the haze of an autumn twilight","From a distant felt tent a thread of smoke rises","Like a dark-gold peony from his native Hanzhong","Slowly blooming across the sky of the Western Regions","","He turns to gaze at that dark-gold cloud far to the west","The flock surges like waves beneath his horse","O, glorious setting sun","Already it has tumbled","Beyond the dark-gold horizon","","Yet that glorious arrow must still be in flight","Cast toward the distant west","Cast toward the distant road ahead","Cast toward the vast plains","Of the Great Yuezhi, longed for day and night"],"annotations":[{"term":"Zhang Qian","note":"Zhang Qian (c. 164–114 BC) — Han Dynasty diplomat and explorer who pioneered the Silk Road route to Central Asia on behalf of Emperor Wu."},{"term":"Hujia","note":"Hujia — an ancient reed instrument of northern nomadic peoples, known for its desolate, tragic timbre, often used as a trope in frontier poetry."},{"term":"Great Yuezhi","note":"Great Yuezhi — a nomadic people originally from the Hexi Corridor, later migrated to Central Asia. They were Zhang Qian's destination in seeking an alliance against the Xiongnu."},{"term":"Han Staff","note":"Han Staff (jié) — the imperial envoy's staff of authority, a bamboo rod topped with yak-tail tassels symbolizing the emperor's mandate and mission."}]},{"id":"poem-1-2","title":"The Clasped Hands Slowly Loosened / The Tear-Filled Eyes Abruptly Turned Away","lines":["The boundless steppe has fallen asleep","Snow-crowned Qilian has fallen asleep","The child in the felt tent must have fallen asleep too","","Standing before the black steed","Gazing in silence","At his weeping wife of the Western Regions","Zhang Qian also weeps","Tear-filled eyes meet tear-filled eyes","Hands clasp hands tightly","","Her curling, tawny hair drifts in the breeze","In the pale moonlight","In the pale starlight","Her eyes, blue as Lake Qinghai, gleam with tears","Pale as the moonlight","Pale as the starlight","","Her tears, ripe as grapes, fall","Reflecting the pale moonlight","Reflecting the pale starlight","","The black steed stamps the grass without ceasing","Its sound oppressive","A heavy sheepskin water-bag","And a tall stack of dried naan still hang from the saddle","","Zhang Qian gazes in silence at","His weeping wife","Gazes in silence at","The wife of the Western Regions with whom he has lived for years","","The clasped hands slowly loosen","The tear-filled eyes abruptly turn away"],"annotations":[{"term":"Qilian Mountains","note":"Qilian Mountains — located at the border of Gansu and Qinghai, meaning 'Heavenly Mountain' in Xiongnu. It is the southern barrier of the Hexi Corridor and an ancient crucial passage to the Western Regions."}]},{"id":"poem-1-3","title":"O Great Yuezhi / The Holy Land He Has Dreamed of for Eleven Springs","lines":["How long he has been riding, he does not know","Whether he is still riding, he is not sure","In the darkness, not even the dim horizon is visible","Nothing is visible","All seems frozen in the profound dark","","Still he presses on with all his strength","The distance between him and Tangyi Fu slowly narrows","But where is the mysterious Great Yuezhi?","Where is the distant Great Yuezhi?","","Just follow loyal, capable Tangyi Fu","Just ride into the pitch-black west","One day they shall reach their destination","","O Great Yuezhi","The holy land he has dreamed of for eleven springs","Through more than four thousand unbearable days in foreign lands","The name he murmured ceaselessly","Through more than four thousand unbearable nights in foreign lands","The name he murmured ceaselessly","","From the galloping saddle he turns once more","To gaze at a silhouette already lost from sight"],"annotations":[{"term":"Tangyi Fu","note":"Tangyi Fu — Zhang Qian's loyal Xiongnu companion and guide throughout his perilous journey to the Western Regions."}]},{"id":"poem-1-4","title":"Bathed in the Cool Radiance / That Daylight Had Yearned for Like Shade","lines":["That tyrannous sun —","When did it sheathe its scorching golden arrows?","A crescent moon above the distant western Tianshan","Smiles at him tenderly","","Waking from a burning, dreadful dream","He bathes in the cool, liquid light","Bathes in the cool radiance","That daylight had yearned for like shade","","He clenches his fist ever tighter","The icy grains of sand","Trickle slowly through his fingers to the ground","He can hear the soft rustling sound","As though the mountain stream of home flows again before him","Moistening his gaunt cheeks","Moistening his cracked lips"]},{"id":"poem-1-5","title":"The Pioneer of the Silk Road Smiled from Horseback / Gazing Westward","lines":["No longer narrow as the Hexi Corridor","No longer a winding trail","Hemmed between chains of mountains","","Gazing into the distance","Slowly riding west","As though on a ship of the Gobi","As though listening to the distant melody of camel bells","Nothing obstructs the view","","O, the new continent of Central Asia","Mysterious and vast","Has miraculously","Appeared before the explorer bearing the Han envoy's staff","","Zhang Qian smiled","The pioneer of the Silk Road smiled from horseback","Gazing westward","Gazing toward the still-unseen","Direction of the Great Yuezhi","From his cracked lips, crimson drops of blood trickled down","","April 1984","(Published in *The Writer*, Issue 5, 1985)"],"annotations":[{"term":"Hexi Corridor","note":"Hexi Corridor — a narrow passage located in northwestern Gansu between the Qilian and Beishan mountains. It was the crucial throat connecting the Central Plains to the Western Regions and a key segment of the Silk Road."},{"term":"Silk Road","note":"Silk Road — the ancient network of trade routes connecting China to Central and West Asia, and Europe, named for the Chinese silk that was heavily traded westward."}]}]},{"id":"chapter-2","title":"Beneath Qilian, Silence Has Fallen","poems":[{"id":"poem-2-1","title":"He Kept His Eyes Fixed / On the Distant Icy Peaks of Qilian","lines":["The iron torrent flows slowly","The great desert flows slowly","Gazing from horseback","He can no longer bear to see","The ash-brown flickering like flame","","He keeps his eyes fixed","On the distant icy peaks of Qilian","So crystalline and cool","They chill to the marrow","Floating on the surging, ash-brown clouds","Now and then flashing a blue, spectral light","Like a verdant mirage","Shimmering always on the horizon","","Huo Qubing licked his cracked lips","Licked the beading blood"],"annotations":[{"term":"Huo Qubing","note":"Huo Qubing (140–117 BC) — brilliant young Han general who defeated the Xiongnu at Qilian, securing the Hexi Corridor. He died prematurely at age 24."}]},{"id":"poem-2-2","title":"Is That the Long-Dreamed Crescent Moon Lake? / The Crescent Lake That Once Graced His Dreams?","lines":["Still galloping","Into the deep night","Only the drumming of hooves","Mingling with the wind's drizzle","","Dunhuang in March","The wind is still biting","Iron-grey thickets, not yet budding with elm coins,","Steeped in darkness, sweep past","Wave-like iron-grey dunes sweep past","Their outlines so faint","The night sky, too, is iron-grey","","Wild pigeons startle into flight","Those startled pigeons are iron-grey too","The beating of their wings fades in an instant","","Ahead, a crescent moon rises","In the iron-grey night sky","Glimmering with a pale, spectral light","","Is that the Crescent Moon Lake he has long dreamed of?","The crescent lake that once graced his dreams?"],"annotations":[{"term":"Dunhuang","note":"Dunhuang — an ancient oasis city at the westernmost end of the Hexi Corridor, a hub of the ancient Silk Road, world-renowned for its Mogao Caves."},{"term":"Crescent Lake","note":"Crescent Lake (Yueyaquan) — located at the foot of the Mingsha Mountains in Dunhuang, named for its crescent moon shape, historically praised as 'the first spring in the desert'."}]},{"id":"poem-2-3","title":"The Carrier Pigeon Circled Hurriedly for a Moment / Then Flew Eastward","lines":["The soldier had just fallen","When he hastily tore open his black tunic","A carrier pigeon rose from his breast","His hot blood","Had already stained the white plumage crimson","Still glistening wet","","Skimming past the steeds that galloped by the soldier","Past the sand-grains lifted like mist","Past the overcast sky, dull as sand","Soaring upward","","Lying face-up on the embattled earth","Iron cavalry thundering across his body","Like storm clouds sweeping before his eyes","His clenched hands go slack","Yet his eyes still gaze at the vast heavens","","The carrier pigeon circled hurriedly for a moment","Then flew eastward","Across the reflection in his pupils — of flashing blades and gleaming swords —","It cast a dark-brown shadow"]},{"id":"poem-2-4","title":"O, Son of the Tianshan / Torrent of Snow-Melt","lines":["In the spring breeze","The young general's crimson cloak","Rises like a red cloud from the saddle","","Even the retreating enemy riders turn to look —","As though a red lotus had bloomed","On the darkened horizon","","O, son of the Tianshan","Torrent of snow-melt","Even the Qilian Mountains tremble","At the war drum in your breast","","Four hundred leagues of wilderness spring into green","In the wake of galloping hooves"]},{"id":"poem-2-5","title":"His Phantom-Like Black Steed / Stands Frozen as a Statue Beneath Qilian","lines":["Beneath Qilian, silence has fallen","His phantom-like black steed","Stands frozen as a statue beneath Qilian","Beneath Qilian, all is silent","","He still gazes at the icy peak before him","So crystalline and cool","As though that peak were his eternal monument","","He still gazes at the grasslands before him","Boundless as the sea","As though those grasslands were his eternal bed","","The wind whispers against his crimson cloak","Like the rustling of silk banners","Like the murmur of his mother's lullaby","","He was only twenty-four when he","Let the reins slip from his fingers","Only twenty-four","When he closed his eyes for the last time","","But the war drum in his breast still thunders","Thunder upon thunder","Resounding through the Hexi Corridor","Through the vast deserts and grasslands of the Western Regions","","His phantom-like black steed","Still stands beneath Qilian","Like a sculpture","Motionless as a mountain","The earth is silent","Beneath Qilian, silence has fallen"]},{"id":"poem-2-6","title":"Standing in the Wine-Sweet, Dark-Gold Sunset / Standing in the Future Bazaars of the Silk Road","lines":["The setting sun paused a moment before slipping away","Still gilding the young general's bronze cheeks","The wind-worn, time-struck features of his face","Still bore the flush of that last battle","","His war horse bent down to drink from the spring","Ripples spread across the water","Like the silk road unfurling toward the west","","Standing in the wine-sweet, dark-gold sunset","He could smell the fragrance drifting from the future","The mingled scent of grapes and pomegranates","From bazaars not yet built","","Standing in the future bazaars of the Silk Road","Standing in streets paved with moonlight and camel bells","He raised the bronze goblet","Let the wine of Jiuquan pour like gold","Into the spring that the emperor had named for him","For his soldiers to share, one sip at a time","","The spring flows on","Even now, still fragrant","At the foot of Qilian","In the wine-sweet sunset"],"annotations":[{"term":"Jiuquan","note":"Jiuquan ('Wine Spring') — a city in Gansu named after a legend that General Huo Qubing poured imperial wine into a spring to share it with all his troops."}]}]},{"id":"chapter-3","title":"Wild Poppies","poems":[{"id":"poem-3-1","title":"Beneath the Galloping Hooves / Waves of Wild Poppies Unfurl","lines":["She rides from the deep grassland","From blooming wild poppies, jade-green and crimson","Her braids streaming behind her","Like two young swallows in flight","","Beneath the galloping hooves","Waves of wild poppies unfurl","Crimson and boundless as the sunset","Stretching in every direction","","The young Wusun princess","Daughter of the grassland","Galloping toward the setting sun","With the wind in her face","","How far away the Central Plains must be","Yet flowers of the Central Plains bloom here too","There are no walls on this steppe","Only wild poppies","Blooming ceaselessly","","And the Ili River, winding southward","Carrying crimson petals","Through the valley","Into the distance"],"annotations":[{"term":"Künes","note":"Künes — an alpine meadow in the middle section of the Tianshan Mountains (Xinyuan County, Ili, Xinjiang), rich in water and grass, the core pasture of the ancient Wusun State."},{"term":"Princess Xijun","note":"Liu Xijun — daughter of Liu Jian, King of Jiangdu in the Western Han. In 105 BC, Emperor Wu sent her to marry the Wusun King (Kunmo) in a political alliance."},{"term":"Wusun","note":"Wusun — an ancient nomadic kingdom located in the Ili River valley (modern Kazakhstan/Xinjiang) that allied with the Han Dynasty through marriage diplomacy."}]},{"id":"poem-3-2","title":"The July Night Is / So Hushed and Still","lines":["The July night is","So hushed and still","Even the Ili River has quieted its murmur","","On the moonlit steppe","Wild poppies glow","Their crimson petals glistening with dew","Like tears she has not yet shed","","She stands beneath the Tianshan moon","This girl sent from Chang'an","Homesick for the south","","But the grassland wind","Already smells of home — of earth","She cannot tell whether it is the steppe or her heart that sighs"],"annotations":[{"term":"Ili River","note":"Ili River — major river flowing from the Tianshan Mountains into Lake Balkhash, historically the cradle of Wusun and Kazakh cultures."}]},{"id":"poem-3-3","title":"A Dark-Brown Wild Poppy Has Withered / Yet Its Petals Still Release a Heady Fragrance","lines":["A dark-brown wild poppy has withered","Yet its petals still release a heady fragrance","","Time has turned the crimson to brown","Yet cannot erase the perfume","","She pressed the petals between the pages","Of a letter she would send to Chang'an","But there was no courier to the east","No wild goose that far","","So the fragrance stayed","Stayed in the valley of the Ili","Stayed in the windswept steppe","Even now, two thousand years later"]},{"id":"poem-3-4","title":"Before Her, the Ili River / Has No Trace of That Crimson Leaf That Carried Her Childhood Heart","lines":["On the day she left Chang'an","A child pressed a red leaf into her hand","She placed it on the water of the Wei River","And watched it drift westward","","Through the Hexi Corridor","Through the Jade Gate Pass","Across deserts she had never imagined","The leaf in her memory kept drifting","","She never saw that leaf again —","That red leaf carrying her childhood heart","Before her, the Ili River","Has no trace of that crimson leaf","Only the fallen petals of wild poppies","Though they too are red","","The Wusun king is old","His felt tent smells of mutton and fermented mare's milk","Through the tent flap she can see","The snow-covered Tianshan","","Her childhood is buried in Chang'an","Her girlhood lost along the road","Here at the edge of the known world","She is a princess with no kingdom to return to","","Before her, the Ili River flows on","Carrying wild poppy petals","Though they too are red","They are not her crimson leaf"]},{"id":"poem-3-5","title":"The Mournful Phrases of Her 'Song of Longing for Home' / Still Echo","lines":["My family married me to the edge of the sky —","Her song drifts from two thousand years ago","Over the steppe, over the river","","My dwelling is a felt tent, its walls of wool","My food is flesh, my drink is milk —","The words she sang have seeped into the earth","Into the roots of every wild poppy","","I long to be a yellow swan","Returning to my homeland —","But the yellow swan does not fly eastward","It circles above the Ili River","Above the snow peaks of the Tianshan","And weeps","","Princess Xijun's song is","The first poem of the Silk Road","Written not in ink","But in tears and wild poppy petals","","Two thousand years later","The crimson Keziaerdake flowers","Still bloom on the banks of the Ili","As though her tears","Have become seeds","","The mournful phrases of her 'Song of Longing for Home'","Still echo","Through every spring","When the wild poppies bloom once more"],"annotations":[{"term":"Song of Homesickness","note":"Song of Sorrow — composed by Princess Xijun, expressing deep lament over being married off to an alien, distant land. It is the earliest recorded 'Heqin' (marriage alliance) poem in Chinese literary history."},{"term":"Yellow Swan","note":"Yellow Swan — referenced in Princess Xijun's Song of Sorrow, reading 'I wish I were a yellow swan, returning to my hometown.' It has since become a classic literary trope for homesickness."},{"term":"Kizil Ardak Flower","note":"Kizil Ardak — meaning 'red flower' in Kazakh, referring to the wild tulips common in the Ili River Valley of Xinjiang that bloom fiery red in spring."}]}]},{"id":"chapter-4","title":"Blood-Sweating Horses","poems":[{"id":"poem-4-1","title":"The Commander on Horseback / A Bitter Smile Crosses His Lips","lines":["Sixty thousand troops set out toward the west","Bound for a kingdom most had never heard of","Bound for horses that sweated blood","","Li Guangli, the Ershi General —","Brother of the emperor's beloved consort","A man more accustomed to the court than the saddle","Now master of an army stretched thin as silk","","The first campaign collapsed","Before it reached the walls of Dayuan","Starved, thirsty, beaten by the desert","He limped back to Dunhuang","With barely a tenth of his men","","A bitter smile crosses his lips","For the emperor's edict awaits:","Return. Bring back the horses. Or do not return at all.","","He gazes at the Pamir snowcaps","At the sky above the Tarim","At the fallen soldiers whose bones","Mark the road like milestones","","The blood-sweating horses of Dayuan —","Were they worth all this?","The emperor says they are.","The dead cannot answer.","","He tightens the reins","The army marches west again","Sixty thousand once more","Into the furnace of heaven"],"annotations":[{"term":"Li Guangli","note":"Li Guangli — Western Han general commissioned by Emperor Wu, who led two immense expeditions to Dayuan (104–101 BC) to obtain the famed 'blood-sweating' horses."},{"term":"Blood-Sweating Horses","note":"Blood-Sweating Horses — the legendary Akhal-Teke horses of Fergana. Their skin was said to 'sweat blood' during intense exertion."},{"term":"Dayuan","note":"Dayuan (Fergana) — an ancient kingdom in the Fergana Valley of Central Asia, famous for breeding the high-quality 'blood-sweating' Akhal-Teke horses."},{"term":"Pamir Mountains","note":"Pamir Mountains — located in southeastern Central Asia, historically known as the 'Onion Range', it was the highest barrier crossed by the ancient Silk Road connecting China and Central Asia."}]},{"id":"poem-4-2","title":"Then Suddenly Froze Amid the Flood of Men / Frozen into the Shape of a Blood-Sweating Horse, Neighing Skyward","lines":["The gates of Dayuan opened at last","Not to diplomacy, but to the sword","Inside the walls, the fabled horses","Stamped and snorted in their stalls","","Their flanks glistened with crimson moisture","As though they wept blood in the heat","The soldiers stared","These were the horses the emperor dreamed of?","","Three thousand horses were led out","Their hooves striking the stone road","Like a drumroll from the heart of the earth","","One horse reared suddenly amid the flood of men","Frozen into the shape of a blood-sweating horse","Neighing at the sky","As though even it knew the price that had been paid"]},{"id":"poem-4-3","title":"Toward the Distant West / Toward the Unforgettable West","lines":["The long march home","Three thousand horses in a river of dust","Through the Wuzi Bieli pass","Through the iron-cold nights of the Pamir","","The horses of Dayuan, unaccustomed to this land","Stumbled on the gravel of the Taklamakan","Some fell and did not rise","Their blood seeping into the sand","— Red as the sweat they once shed when they ran","","The soldiers sang no songs on this road","They had sung them all on the way out","Now only the wind sang","And the distant creaking of the supply carts","","Li Guangli counted the horses each dawn","Each dawn the number was smaller","As though the desert were drinking them","","He thought of the Amu River","Where the water was sweet and the grass was green","Where the Yuezhi people once grazed their flocks","Before Zhang Qian came, before anyone came","","Toward the distant west","Toward the unforgettable west","He had traveled with the force of empire behind him","And now he returned","With an empire's worth of grief ahead","","How many horses would survive to reach Chang'an?","How many soldiers?","The blood-sweating horses of Dayuan","Had no answer","They simply walked on","Toward the east","Their crimson sweat drying in the desert wind","Like the last ink on a silk letter","That no one would read"],"annotations":[{"term":"Taklamakan Desert","note":"Taklamakan Desert — China's largest desert, located in the Tarim Basin of Xinjiang. In Uyghur, it allegedly means 'place from which there is no return', spanning around 330,000 square kilometers."},{"term":"Uzbel Pass","note":"Uzbel Pass — an important mountain pass on the Pamir Plateau, located on the border between China and Kyrgyzstan, it was a western exit of the ancient Silk Road."},{"term":"Amu Darya","note":"Amu Darya — the longest river in Central Asia, historically Guishui. The Great Yuezhi settled in the Amu Darya basin after migrating westward."}]},{"id":"poem-4-4","title":"Already He Can See / The Solemn, Gentle Towers of Chang'an","lines":["Already he can see —","Or thinks he can —","The solemn, gentle towers of Chang'an","","The emperor waits at the Xuanwu Gate","His ministers in their silken robes","The incense burners sending blue spirals skyward","","Of the three thousand blood-sweating horses","Only a thousand have survived the road","Their flanks still glistening","But now more bone than muscle","","The emperor will compose his 'Song of the Heavenly Horses' —","'Their spirit is extraordinary, their power divine' —","And have it performed with bells and jade chimes","","But Li Guangli will remember","Not the bells","But the sound of horses falling in the sand","Not the jade chimes","But the silence after the last soldier's cry","","The blood-sweating horses of Dayuan","Now stand in the imperial stables","Their crimson sweat still beading","Like the tears of every man who did not return"],"annotations":[{"term":"Emperor Wu of Han","note":"Emperor Wu (Liu Che, 156–87 BC) — the seventh emperor of the Western Han. A visionary ruler who expanded the empire westward and dispatched Zhang Qian to open the Silk Road."},{"term":"Song of the Heavenly Horses from the Western Extremity","note":"Song of the Heavenly Horses — a Yuefu poem composed personally by Emperor Wu of Han after obtaining the blood-sweating horses, praising their majestic spirit to express his grand imperial ambitions."}]}]},{"id":"chapter-5","title":"Loulan Vanished in an Instant","poems":[{"id":"poem-5-1","title":"Prostrate beside Lop Nur / Prostrate beneath the Bonfire of the High Altar","lines":["Prostrate beside Lop Nur","Prostrate beneath the bonfire of the high altar","The priest of Loulan chants in an unknown tongue","His shadow stretching into the salt flats","","Where did the water go?","The lake that once mirrored the Kunlun peaks","Now only salt crystals","Cracking like the bones of fish","","The poplar forests still stand","Hollow and skeletal","Dead a thousand years but still upright","As though waiting for the water to return","","Loulan vanished in an instant —","Not by sword or fire","But by the slow turning of a river's course","","Even empires cannot command","The path water chooses","Even prayers cannot summon","Rain from an empty sky"],"annotations":[{"term":"Lop Nur","note":"Lop Nur — once a vast salt lake in eastern Xinjiang, now a completely dry lake bed. It was the site of the ancient Loulan ruins and later China's nuclear testing ground."},{"term":"Desert Poplar","note":"Desert Poplar (Populus euphratica) — a highly drought and salt-resistant deciduous tree found around the Taklamakan Desert. It is said to 'live a thousand years, stand dead for a thousand years, and remain un-rotted for a thousand years'."},{"term":"Tamarisk","note":"Tamarisk (Red Willow) — a common shrub or small tree in northwestern deserts, highly resistant to salt and drought, serving as a crucial plant for windbreaks and sand fixation."},{"term":"Loulan","note":"Loulan — an ancient Silk Road kingdom near Lop Nur that mysteriously vanished around the 4th century AD primarily due to desertification and changing river courses."}]},{"id":"poem-5-2","title":"This Seed Gathered from the Forests of Lop Nur / Still Damp with Night Dew","lines":["This seed gathered from the forests of Lop Nur","Still damp with night dew","He carried it a thousand leagues to the east","Wrapped in a scrap of Loulan silk","","If planted in Chang'an's soil","Would it grow?","Would it remember the salt-crusted shore?","The cry of migrating birds?","","The merchant from Loulan","Stood at the crossroads of civilizations","Where silk went west and jade came east","Where languages tangled in the bazaar","","He pressed the seed to his cheek","It was cool, like the nights by the lake","Cool, like the skin of his daughter","Whom he had left behind","","That daughter now plays","Among the ruins of a kingdom","That will not be found","For another eighteen hundred years"]},{"id":"poem-5-3","title":"O, Let the Immortal Sound of Lop Nur's Waves / Echo Forever in the Dreams of the Homeland","lines":["O, let the immortal sound of Lop Nur's waves","Echo forever in the dreams of the homeland","","Though the waves have long since stilled","Though the lake bed crackles underfoot","Somewhere beneath the salt","The memory of water persists","","Like a song the sand refuses to forget","Like a road the wind cannot erase","","Let the poplar's ghost stand witness","Let the tamarisk hold the dune in place","Until the river, in some far century,","Remembers its old path","And flows back to Loulan"]},{"id":"poem-5-4","title":"Crescent-Shaped Lop Nur / Already Set at the Far Edge of a Distant Sky","lines":["Where the caravans once rested","Where the jade was weighed and the silk was folded","Where the storyteller told of mountains to the west","And seas beyond those mountains","","Now only wind","Only the dry rattle of dead branches","Only the yardang ridges","Carved by centuries of grit","","Crescent-shaped Lop Nur","Already set at the far edge of a distant sky","No longer a lake","But a memory of a lake","","The explorer from Sweden came","And brushed the sand from Loulan's face","And the world gasped","At the beautiful dead","","Her eyelashes still perfect","After four thousand years beneath the salt","The Loulan Beauty","Sleeping on","In a glass case in Ürümqi","","While the wind still blows","Over the place she was born","Where nothing grows","Where nothing stirs","But the memory of water and light"]}]},{"id":"chapter-6","title":"O, at Lake Baikal Autumn Is Already Deep","poems":[{"id":"poem-6-1","title":"The Green Flame of the Mountain Pasture / Already Burns in the Herdsman's Heart","lines":["Nineteen years at the shore of the North Sea","Nineteen years with a staff of withered bamboo","Its yak-tail pennant long since frayed to nothing","","Su Wu tends his flock of rams","On the frozen shore of Lake Baikal","Where no envoy comes","Where no message arrives from the south","","Yet every spring","When the ice breaks and the green flame","Of new grass sweeps across the steppe","He feels it burn in his heart too","","The green flame of the mountain pasture","Already burns in the herdsman's heart","Not the heart of a herdsman — no —","The heart of a Han envoy","Who will not yield","","His robes have rotted to rags","His hair has silvered like the birch bark","But the staff he carries","Though bare of pennant and authority","He will not set down","","Nineteen years","The lake has frozen and thawed nineteen times","And still he waits"],"annotations":[{"term":"Lake Baikal","note":"Lake Baikal — the deepest and oldest freshwater lake in the world, located in Siberia. It is the historical \"North Sea\" where Han envoy Su Wu was exiled to tend sheep."},{"term":"Su Wu","note":"Su Wu — a Han Dynasty envoy (c. 140–60 BC) who was held captive by the Xiongnu for 19 years at Lake Baikal, famously clutching his Han imperial staff and refusing to surrender."}]},{"id":"poem-6-2","title":"Kissing This Handful of Earth for a Long Time / His Longing Eyes Gently Closed","lines":["When they told him he could go home","He did not believe them at first","Nineteen years of silence","Had taught him not to trust words","","But then the southern envoy showed him","The emperor's seal","And something broke inside him","Like the spring ice shattering on the lake","","He knelt on the frozen ground","And scooped up a handful of Baikal earth","Black and cold and smelling of pine","","Kissing this handful of earth for a long time","His longing eyes gently closed","He whispered to it:","I am leaving you now","But I will never forget","The sound of your wind on winter nights","","He placed the earth in his sleeve","Beside the worn-bare staff","And turned south","","The flock of rams watched him go","Bleating softly","As though they too understood","What it means to be faithful"]},{"id":"poem-6-3","title":"Standing on the Shore of Crystalline Baikal / Like a Stern Iceberg","lines":["Li Ling came to see him at the farewell feast","Li Ling — grandson of the Flying General","Li Ling — who had also fought and lost","And could never go home","","They drank in silence","Two old men who had been young warriors","Two men who had served the same emperor","One who bent, one who did not","","Li Ling said: Stay with me.","The Xiongnu princess treats me well.","I have sons now. A warm tent.","","Su Wu looked at him","Standing on the shore of crystalline Baikal","Like a stern iceberg","And said nothing","","Then he raised his cup","And drank to the south wind","And Li Ling wept","Not for Su Wu's departure","But for his own inability to follow","","They parted at the lake's edge","One riding south with a bare staff","One remaining with a borrowed name"],"annotations":[{"term":"Li Ling","note":"Li Ling — grandson of the famous Han general Li Guang. He surrendered to the Xiongnu after fighting heroically until his arrows ran out, a surrender that remained deeply controversial."}]},{"id":"poem-6-4","title":"That Wild Goose Flew from His Hand / From His Blood-Stained Hand","lines":["The legend says","A wild goose carried his message home","That the emperor's hunters shot it from the sky","And found a silk letter tied to its leg","","Su Wu is alive, the letter said","He is at the North Sea","He is waiting","","That wild goose flew from his hand","From his blood-stained hand","Across the Gobi","Across the Yellow River","Across the years","","And Chang'an heard","And remembered","A man it had given up for dead","","When Su Wu walked through the city gates at last","White-haired, thin as a ghost","Still clutching his bare staff","The emperor wept","The ministers wept","The common people lined the streets and wept","","Not because he was a hero","But because he had simply","Refused to forget","Who he was"],"annotations":[{"term":"Swan Goose","note":"Swan Goose — in legend, a Han envoy bluffed the Xiongnu by claiming the Emperor shot down a goose with a letter from Su Wu tied to its leg, securing Su Wu's release. Thus 'swan goose' became a metaphor for postal letters."}]}]},{"id":"chapter-7","title":"In the Vast Yarkand","poems":[{"id":"poem-7-1","title":"The Flock of Doves Circling Above Yangguan / Still Circles in Her Eyes","lines":["The flock of doves circling above Yangguan","Still circles in her eyes","The Silk Princess hides her secret","In the golden crown upon her head","","She carries the silkworm eggs westward","Past the Jade Gate, past the sentries","Past the desert where only wind lives","","In the vast Yarkand","The mulberry trees will soon be planted","And silk will flow","Like a river of light","From the looms of the Western Regions","","Who taught the West to weave?","A princess who loved a foreign king","And smuggled the seeds of civilization","In her wedding headdress","","At Yangguan, the doves still circle","As though searching","For a girl who passed through long ago"],"annotations":[{"term":"Yarkand","note":"Yarkand — an ancient Western Regions location, present-day Shache County in Xinjiang. The Yarkand River is one of the main tributaries of the Tarim River."},{"term":"Silk Princess","note":"Silk Princess — a legendary Central Plains princess who hid silkworm eggs in her royal headdress when married off to the King of Khotan, thus smuggling sericulture technology into the Western Regions."},{"term":"Yangguan Pass","note":"Yangguan Pass — a Han Dynasty border fortress southwest of Dunhuang, an essential checkpoint on the southern route of the Silk Road. Made famous by Wang Wei's poem 'West of Yangguan is no old friend'."}]},{"id":"poem-7-2","title":"That Ash-Brown Horizon / Moving Slowly Forward","lines":["That ash-brown horizon","Moving slowly forward","As the camel train advances","Through the shimmer of heat","","The road stretches on","Beyond what the eye can hold","Beyond what the heart can bear","","She looks back once","At the towers receding into dust","At the land she will never see again","","Then forward, only forward","Through the ash-brown haze","Into the unknown kingdom","Of Khotan"]},{"id":"poem-7-3","title":"The Crescent Moon Above the Great Mosque / May Also Glow with a Pale, Mysterious Radiance","lines":["The crescent moon above the great mosque","May also glow with a pale, mysterious radiance","Above the minarets of Yarkand","","Where silk and jade have made","A city of many faiths","A crossroads of prayers","In every tongue that travels the road","","The muezzin calls at dusk","And the silk weavers pause","Their shuttles stilled","Beneath the crescent moon","In the vast Yarkand"]},{"id":"poem-7-4","title":"That Song Dissolves into the Waves of the Yarkand River / And the Symphony of Rustling Mulberry Groves","lines":["She taught them to unwind the cocoon","Thread by thread, patient as prayer","The women of Khotan learned quickly","Their dark fingers nimble on the loom","","From the mulberry groves that she had planted","The silkworms spun their golden thread","And Khotan silk, they say,","Rivaled even Chang'an's finest","","That song dissolves into the waves","Of the Yarkand River","And the symphony of rustling mulberry groves","Where every leaf remembers","A princess far from home","","Century after century","The looms of Khotan wove on","Until the sand swallowed them","And only the song remained","Drifting in the desert wind","Like a silk thread unraveling"]},{"id":"poem-7-5","title":"The Amber Glow of Silk / Shining in King Axihan's Amber-Colored Dream","lines":["King Axihan of Khotan","Stood at his city gate","Gazing east toward the shimmering road","","He had asked for a bride from the Han court","And they had sent him a princess","With a secret sewn into her crown","","The amber glow of silk","Shining in Axihan's amber-colored dream","A vision of his kingdom","Draped in luminous thread","","When the crown was opened","And the tiny eggs were found","He did not punish her","He thanked her","","For she had brought not just herself","But an entire civilization's craft","Wrapped in love and cunning","","The mulberry groves spread across Khotan","The silkworms multiplied","And the Silk Road earned its name","Not from merchants alone","But from a princess","Who dared to smuggle dreams","","At the foot of the Kunlun Mountains","The silk still gleams","In the amber light of sunset","In the Yarkand River's last reflection","Before the desert drinks it dry"],"annotations":[{"term":"Asikhan","note":"Asikhan — the legendary King of Khotan (Yutian) who married the Silk Princess that smuggled the silkworm seeds from the Central Plains."}]}]},{"id":"chapter-8","title":"The Beacon-Fires Have Died","poems":[{"id":"poem-8-1","title":"Drowning Out Even the Thunderous Hoofbeats / Like a Storm","lines":["Thirty-six men rode into the Western Regions","Led by Ban Chao, a scholar turned soldier","A man who had traded the brush for the sword","Who said: 'He who does not enter the tiger's den / Cannot catch the tiger's cub'","","At Shanshan, the first test came","The Xiongnu envoys had arrived before him","Outnumbering his men ten to one","","That night he lit fires around the Xiongnu camp","And his men roared like an army of thousands","Drowning out even the thunderous hoofbeats","Like a storm descending","","By dawn, the Xiongnu envoys were dead","And the King of Shanshan","Knelt before the Han flag","","Ban Chao smiled","As a scholar smiles","When the right character finally","Falls into place","","Thirty years he stayed in the western lands","Thirty years with thirty-six men","Who became an empire's shield","At the edge of the world","","The beacon-fires he lit","Along the old Silk Road","Burned for three decades","Then died, one by one"],"annotations":[{"term":"Ban Chao","note":"Ban Chao (32–102 AD) — a legendary Eastern Han general and diplomat who, with only 36 men, re-established Chinese suzerainty across the Western Regions over a 31-year campaign."},{"term":"Shanshan","note":"Shanshan — a Silk Road kingdom (formerly Loulan); the site of Ban Chao's daring night raid on a Xiongnu delegation, his first major victory in the Western Regions."}]},{"id":"poem-8-2","title":"As Though a Hundred Thousand Armored Men / A Mournful, Desolate Melody Flows","lines":["In his old age, Ban Chao asked to go home","His letter to the emperor read:","'I dare not hope to reach Jiuquan alive","I only wish my bones may cross the Jade Gate'","","The emperor read and wept","And granted his wish","","As though a hundred thousand armored men","A mournful, desolate melody flows","Through the pass, through the corridor","Through the thirty years of exile","","He died within a month of his return","As though his body had been waiting","Only for the sight of home"]},{"id":"poem-8-3","title":"Already Locked in Close Combat / Killing in Silence","lines":["After Ban Chao left, the beacons dimmed","The small garrisons grew smaller","Already locked in close combat","Killing in silence","","Without his presence","The Western Regions fractured","Kingdom by kingdom","Like a string of jade beads","Whose thread has snapped","","The silence after Ban Chao","Was louder than any battle","The silence of an empire retreating","From the world's edge"]},{"id":"poem-8-4","title":"The Morning Star Is Fading / The Beacon-Fires Have Died","lines":["The morning star is fading","The beacon-fires have died","Along the road from Dunhuang to Kashgar","Only wind moves now","","The watchtowers crumble","Their smoke signals long extinguished","The sentries have gone home","Or been buried in the sand","","But the road remains","Worn into the earth by centuries","Of silk and jade and spice","Of armies and monks and merchants","","The morning star is fading","But it will rise again","As it has always risen","Over the passes of the Pamir","Over the plains of Central Asia","","The beacon-fires have died","But the road endures","The road endures","The Silk Road endures","One flame at a time"]}]},{"id":"chapter-9","title":"The Dark-Blue Persian Gulf","poems":[{"id":"poem-9-1","title":"Praying in Silence toward the Distant West / That Holy Land","lines":["Gan Ying stood at the edge of the known world","Where the land ended and the sea began","Praying in silence toward the distant west","That holy land — Rome — Da Qin","","The Parthian merchants shook their heads:","'The sea is vast. The voyage takes months.'","'Many who sail never return.'","","He gazed at the dark-blue water","The waves that separated him from Rome","From the western edge of the Silk Road","From the empire that wore the silk","His own people had woven","","He turned back","The farthest envoy China had sent","Almost — almost — touching Rome","","97 AD","The year a Chinese man","Stood at the Persian Gulf","And could go no farther"],"annotations":[{"term":"Gan Ying","note":"Gan Ying — a Han military envoy dispatched by Ban Chao in 97 AD to establish contact with Da Qin (the Roman Empire). He reached the Persian Gulf but was dissuaded from crossing."}]},{"id":"poem-9-2","title":"Through the Branches Where the Golden Partridges Perched / Heavy Red Rain Falls with a Rustling Sound","lines":["In the gardens of Ctesiphon","Pomegranates hung like lanterns","Through the branches where the golden partridges perched","Heavy red rain falls with a rustling sound","","Gan Ying walked these foreign gardens","Smelling scents he had no names for","Tasting fruit that grew in no Chinese earth","","The Parthian king received him with curiosity","'You come from the land of silk?'","'How far did you walk?'","","Gan Ying calculated in his mind:","From Luoyang to here — forty thousand li","Seven years of walking","Through every kingdom between","","'I have walked,' he said,","'From where the sun rises to where it begins to set.'","","The king laughed","And poured him wine","Dark as the Persian Gulf","Fragrant as a road without end"]},{"id":"poem-9-3","title":"The Wind from the Zagros Mountains, Damp / Blowing toward Him with a Briny Tang","lines":["The wind from the Zagros Mountains, damp","Blowing toward him with a briny tang","Carried whispers of the sea beyond","","He could almost smell Rome","Could almost see its marble columns","Rising from the foam","","But the Parthians would not let him cross","They held the middle of the road","The brokers of silk and glass","Who profited from the distance","Between East and West",""],"annotations":[{"term":"Zagros Mountains","note":"Zagros Mountains — a major mountain range in western Iran, stretching from the Persian Gulf to eastern Turkey, acting as a natural barrier on the Silk Road to Mesopotamia."},{"term":"Persian Gulf","note":"Persian Gulf — an arm of the Arabian Sea between the Arabian Peninsula and southwestern Iran. Gan Ying purportedly reached its shores before abandoning his voyage to Rome."}]},{"id":"poem-9-4","title":"Bitter Seawater Mingled with Bitter Tears / Cast Again into the Dark-Blue Persian Gulf","lines":["He stood at the water's edge a long time","The waves breaking over his worn leather boots","Bitter seawater mingled with bitter tears","Cast again into the dark-blue Persian Gulf","","He had come so far","Across the Pamir's frozen passes","Through the sands of the Taklamakan","Past the ruins of kingdoms","Whose names even scholars had forgotten","","And here, at the threshold of Rome","He was turned back","Not by an army","But by a merchant's lie","","'The sea will take two years,' they said","Knowing it took only weeks","Knowing that if East met West directly","Their middleman's fortune would vanish","","Gan Ying turned east","His shadow falling on the Persian Gulf","The longest shadow China ever cast westward","","He carried back reports","Of glass that could be blown like breath","Of acrobats and fire-swallowers","Of an empire that matched his own","","Two empires, ignorant of each other","Separated by desert and deceit","And one man","Who almost — almost —","Bridged the distance","Standing ankle-deep","In the dark-blue waves","Of the Persian Gulf","In the year 97 AD"]}]},{"id":"chapter-10","title":"Waves of the Tarim River","poems":[{"id":"poem-10-1","title":"His Three Thousand Dunhuang Soldiers / Also Fell Prostrate on the Riverbank","lines":["Suo Le led three thousand men from Dunhuang","Across the burning Taklamakan","To the banks of the Tarim River","","The river was their lifeline —","Dark water rushing from the melting snows","Of mountains they could not see","","His three thousand Dunhuang soldiers","Also fell prostrate on the riverbank","Pressing their faces to the water","Drinking as though they would never drink again","","Then they rose and began to farm","These soldiers who had carried swords","Now carried plows","","The first military farms of the Western Regions","Planted in blood-soaked earth","Irrigated by snowmelt","Guarded by men who missed their homes","","This was the beginning —","The ancestor of the bingtuan","The seed that would grow","Two thousand years later","Into the cities of the frontier"],"annotations":[{"term":"Tarim River","note":"Tarim River — China's longest inland river, stretching about 2,137 kilometers along the northern edge of the Tarim Basin. Historically, the lifeblood of garrison agriculture in the Western Regions."},{"term":"Suo Mai","note":"Suo Mai — an Eastern Han general who led 3,000 troops from Dunhuang to forcibly cross the Tarim River, pioneering large-scale military agricultural colonies (tuntian) in the heart of the Western Regions."},{"term":"Military Reclamation","note":"Military Reclamation — the system of using military troops to cultivate wasteland for agricultural production. Originating in the Han Dynasty's 'tuntian' policy in the Western Regions, it is the historical precedent for the Xinjiang Production and Construction Corps."}]},{"id":"poem-10-2","title":"Eyes Gently Closed / A Green Cloud Drifts from the Distance","lines":["Eyes gently closed","A green cloud drifts from the distance","In his dream, the Tarim shore","Is no longer barren","","Fields of wheat stretch to the horizon","Canals thread through the desert","Like silver veins in stone","","He sees a future he cannot live to see","A future of orchards and cotton","Of roads and schools","Of children who will never know","The sound of sword on shield","","Eyes gently closed","He farms in his dream","The eternal farm","The dream of every soldier","Who wants peace more than glory"]},{"id":"poem-10-3","title":"Merging with the Dark Waves of the Tarim / Surging Ceaselessly under the Pale Moonlight","lines":["At night the river speaks","In a language older than any empire","Merging with the dark waves of the Tarim","Surging ceaselessly under the pale moonlight","","The soldiers listen","Some write letters home","On scraps of wood","In fading ink","","'I am well,' they write","'The harvest was good this year.'","'I planted a poplar tree.'","'It reminds me of the willows by the Wei River.'","","The river carries their voices","Eastward, always eastward","Through the desert night","Through two thousand years"]},{"id":"poem-10-4","title":"Anaerguli on Horseback / Gazing into the Distance","lines":["Anaerguli on horseback","Gazing into the distance","The Uyghur girl rides along the canal","That the Han soldiers dug","","She does not know their names","But drinks the water they channeled","Eats the fruit of trees","Whose ancestors they planted","","The Tarim flows on","Carrying all their stories","Han and Uyghur, soldier and farmer","All drinking from the same river","All gazing at the same moon"]},{"id":"poem-10-5","title":"Still Gazing Down / Still Gazing Down","lines":["From the cliffs above the Tarim","The carved Buddha gazes down","Still gazing down","Still gazing down","","He has seen the armies come and go","The caravans laden with jade","The monks chanting sutras","The farmers planting wheat","","Still gazing down","With the same serene smile","At the river that never stops","At the desert that never sleeps","At the road that never ends","","Two thousand years of gazing","And still the world turns","Beneath his stone eyes","The Tarim flows on","The waves of the Tarim River","Carry all","Carry all"]}]},{"id":"chapter-11","title":"The Mendicant Who Crossed the Border in Secret","poems":[{"id":"poem-11-1","title":"Is This the Night at the Frontier? / So Hushed and Still","lines":["Is this the night at the frontier?","So hushed and still","Only the distant call of a night bird","And the rustle of sand grains shifting","","Xuanzang pressed his body against the cold earth","A fugitive from his own empire","A monk who dared defy the emperor's ban","On leaving the realm","","His crime: to seek the truth","His weapon: a walking staff","His armor: faith","In a land beyond the horizon"],"annotations":[{"term":"Mendicant Monk","note":"Mendicant Monk — referencing the Tang Dynasty monk Xuanzang (602–664). Because he left China illegally in defiance of an imperial travel ban to seek Buddhist scriptures, he was, initially, a stowaway mendicant."}]},{"id":"poem-11-2","title":"Tear-Drops Gleam in the Starlight / So Full of Feeling","lines":["Tear-drops gleam in the starlight","So full of feeling","As the monk looks back one last time","At the dark outline of the Great Wall","","He will not see it again","For seventeen years","Seventeen years of walking","Through the furnace of the desert","Through kingdoms of ice and stone","","Tear-drops gleam in the starlight","Not tears of fear","But of a man who loves his home","So deeply that he must leave it","To bring back something greater"]},{"id":"poem-11-3","title":"The Graceful Flying Apsara / Scatters Rose Petals Damp with Dew","lines":["At the Mogao Caves he prayed","Before the painted apsaras","The graceful flying apsara","Scatters rose petals damp with dew","","Their scarves floating in painted wind","Their smiles eternal on the sandstone walls","They seemed to say: Go.","The road is long but the truth is worth it.","","He lit a candle in the darkness","And touched his forehead to the cold stone floor","Then rose","And walked into the desert","Into the starless night","Into the unknown","Toward India","Toward the sutras","Toward the light he sensed","But could not yet see","","One thousand three hundred thirty-five volumes","He would carry back","One by one","On the back of a single monk"]},{"id":"poem-11-4","title":"Yi Yi Yi / This Is a Cloud Damp with Mist","lines":["Through the Taklamakan he walked","Where mirages danced like cruel promises","Where his water ran dry","And his horse collapsed","","Yi yi yi —","This is a cloud damp with mist","A hallucination","Or a gift from heaven?","","He found water","Or water found him","And he staggered on","Through the burning heart","Of the world's most remorseless desert","Toward Gaochang, toward Kucha","Toward the sound of temple bells"]},{"id":"poem-11-5","title":"He Prays by Moonlight with Eyes Closed / Yet Before Him Floats a Green River","lines":["He prays by moonlight with eyes closed","Yet before him floats a green river","The river of his vision","The river of Buddhist truth","","In Kucha he rested","The king begged him to stay","But the river in his vision flowed on","Westward, always westward","","Past the Tianshan's frozen passes","Past the vultures circling above","Past the limits of the map","Into the unmapped country of the soul"]},{"id":"poem-11-6","title":"The Waves of Issyk-Kul / Still Surging and Splashing in His Mind","lines":["At Issyk-Kul the water was warm","Despite the snow-capped mountains","The waves of Issyk-Kul","Still surging and splashing in his mind","","Yabgu Khan of the Western Turks","Received him with feasts and honor","Offered him guards and horses","And a letter of safe passage","","Xuanzang, the mendicant who crossed the border in secret","Now traveled with an escort fit for an emperor","","From Samarkand to Balkh","From Balkh to Gandhara","From Gandhara to Nalanda","The greatest university the world had known","","He studied there for five years","Debated the masters","Translated the sutras","And wept for joy","","The journey home took another seven years","Through the Pamir, through Kashgar","Through the very desert that had nearly killed him","","But now he carried the scriptures","One thousand three hundred thirty-five volumes","The weight of enlightenment","On the back of a single monk","","Xuanzang — the pilgrim","The mendicant who crossed the border in secret","And returned with a library"],"annotations":[{"term":"Suyab","note":"Suyab — one of the ancient Four Garrisons of Anxi, located near modern Tokmok in Kyrgyzstan. A crucial Tang Dynasty fortress town and famously the purported birthplace of poet Li Bai."},{"term":"Issyk-Kul","note":"Issyk-Kul — a vast endorheic lake in the northern Tian Shan mountains in eastern Kyrgyzstan, the second-largest alpine lake in the world."},{"term":"Yabghu Qaghan","note":"Yabghu Qaghan — ruler of the Western Turkic Khaganate who warmly received Xuanzang in Central Asia, providing him with escorts and diplomatic credentials to continue his westward journey."},{"term":"Xuanzang","note":"Xuanzang (602–664) — a legendary Tang Dynasty Buddhist monk whose 17-year overland pilgrimage to India and meticulous geographic records inspired the classic novel 'Journey to the West'."}]}]},{"id":"chapter-12","title":"The Poet's Soul Still Gallops","poems":[{"id":"poem-12-1","title":"O, No Longer a Solitary Pilgrim / A Warm Current Dispels the Bitter Cold","lines":["Cen Can arrived at the frontier in autumn","When the first snow dusted the Tianshan","O, no longer a solitary pilgrim","A warm current dispels the bitter cold","","For here was a poet among soldiers","A man of brushes amid men of swords","Who saw beauty in the terrible:","","'The north wind sweeps the earth, snapping white grasses,","In the eighth month, snow falls on the Tartar frontier —","Like a spring gale scattering blossoms of pear,'","","His eyes drank the landscape","That terrified other men:","The thousand-league ice sheet","The ten-thousand-league frozen cloud","","He saw them not as hardship","But as grandeur","Not as exile","But as inspiration","","This was the poet of the frontier","Whose verses galloped like warhorses","Across the pages of Tang Dynasty literature","Cen Can — whose soul still gallops","Along the Silk Road","In every line he wrote"],"annotations":[{"term":"Cen Shen","note":"Cen Shen (c. 715–770) — one of the greatest Tang Dynasty frontier poets, celebrated for his majestic, harsh, and vivid depictions of Silk Road landscapes and military campaigns."}]},{"id":"poem-12-2","title":"With the Hand That Had Swung the Saber / He Hastily Caressed the Poem-Pouch at His Waist","lines":["Between battles, he wrote","With the hand that had swung the saber","He hastily caressed the poem-pouch at his waist","That leather satchel where he kept his drafts","","Under the same stars","That Zhang Qian had navigated by","Under the same moon","That Su Wu had wept beneath","","He dipped his brush in battlefield ink","And wrote of snow and fire","Of homesickness and heroism","Of a land so beautiful and so brutal","","That only poetry could contain it","Only verse could hold","The contradictions of the frontier:","Icicles on sword-blades","Spring flowers on gravestones","The cry of a northern flute","In the silence after slaughter"]},{"id":"poem-12-3","title":"The Orange Campfire Still Gleams / A New Star Added to the Night Sky of Central Asia","lines":["The orange campfire still gleams","A new star added to the night sky of Central Asia","Cen Can recites his verses to the soldiers","Who listen with tears in their eyes","","They had not known","That their suffering could be beautiful","That their exile could become legend","That a poet's brush could dignify","Their frozen, bleeding hands","","The campfire crackles","The horses stamp in the cold","And somewhere in the dark beyond","The mountains listen","As they have always listened","To the human voices at their feet","","The orange campfire still gleams","Across twelve hundred years","And will not die"]},{"id":"poem-12-4","title":"So Still You Can Hear / The Poet's Teardrops Falling","lines":["When Cen Can left the frontier","He looked back at the Tianshan","So still you can hear","The poet's teardrops falling","","He had arrived fearing the wilderness","He left loving it","He had arrived a minor official","He left a major poet","","The frontier had forged him","As fire forges steel","The cold, the distance, the loneliness","Had sharpened his verses","Into diamond points","","So still you can hear","Even now","The echo of his brush on paper","In the wind that blows","Through the passes of the Tianshan"]},{"id":"poem-12-5","title":"Like the Crimson Paper-Cut His Wife Made / On Their Wedding Night","lines":["He dreamed of home","Of his wife's face in lamplight","Like the crimson paper-cut his wife made","On their wedding night","","Red as the desert sunset","Delicate as frost on glass","A pattern of paired birds","Of intertwined branches","","He folded the paper-cut","And placed it in his poem-pouch","Next to the verses","Written in frontier snow","","Even now","When you read his poems","You can feel","The warmth of that paper-cut","Against the cold of the frontier","Love pressed against distance","Home carried in a leather satchel","Along the Silk Road"]}]},{"id":"chapter-13","title":"O, the Battle of Talas","poems":[{"id":"poem-13-1","title":"He Seems to See His Cavalry Charging / Along the Banks of the Talas River","lines":["The Battle of Talas, 751 AD","Where the Tang Empire met the Abbasid Caliphate","Where East met West in blood and fire","","He seems to see his cavalry charging","Along the banks of the Talas River","The last great push of Chinese power westward","Into the heartland of Islam","","The battle was lost","The Tang armies broken","The frontier recoiled","Like a snapped bowstring","","But from the prisoners of that battle","The secret of papermaking","Traveled west to Samarkand","To Baghdad, to Cairo, to Europe","","And the world was changed forever","Not by the victor's sword","But by the captive's craft","","The Battle of Talas —","A military defeat","A civilizational triumph"]},{"id":"poem-13-2","title":"Listening to the Unforgettable Summer of Talas / A Requiem So Mournful Yet Tender","lines":["By the Talas River in summer","The poplars cast long shadows","Listening to the unforgettable summer of Talas","A requiem so mournful yet tender","","For the soldiers who fell here","Whose bones became the river's bed","Whose blood nourished the poplars","That still stand sentinel","","Among the prisoners, a papermaker","Who taught his captors the art","Of pressing mulberry bark into sheets","Of spreading knowledge like seed","","The pen he enabled","Would write more history","Than the sword that captured him","","Listen — the Talas River still whispers","The sound of water over paper","The sound of a world transforming","One sheet at a time"]},{"id":"poem-13-3","title":"A Blue-Brown Speck of Light / Sweeping Across the Chaotic Earth and Chaotic Sky","lines":["A blue-brown speck of light","Sweeping across the chaotic earth and chaotic sky","A rider fleeing the battlefield","Carrying in his saddlebag","","Not gold, not jade","But a wooden printing block","Carved with characters","That spell a Buddhist sutra","","He rides through the night","Through the carnage and the smoke","This fragment of civilization","Clutched to his chest","Like a child","","A blue-brown speck of light","Sweeping across the vast darkness","Of an empire in retreat","","But the characters survive","The sutra survives","The written word survives","Everything"]},{"id":"poem-13-4","title":"O, the Crescent Moon and Morning Star / The Crescent Moon and Morning Star of Islam","lines":["After Talas, the crescent moon rose","Over the western reaches of the Silk Road","O, the crescent moon and morning star","The crescent moon and morning star of Islam","","Where Buddhist temples had stood","Mosques would rise","Where Sanskrit was chanted","Arabic would be spoken","","Not conquest — but gradual change","Like the slow turning of a river","The faith came with merchants","Not with armies","","And the Silk Road went on","Under new banners","With new prayers","But the same camel bells","The same starlight","The same human longing","For connection across distance"]},{"id":"poem-13-5","title":"The Light, Urgent Sound of Hoofbeats / Drowned by the Symphony of the Talas River","lines":["The light, urgent sound of hoofbeats","Drowned by the symphony of the Talas River","The retreating army fading into history","","But history does not end","It only turns a page","","On the riverbank a prisoner sits","Making paper for his captors","Sheet by sheet","White as the snow on the Tianshan","Thin as the border between","Victory and defeat","","The light, urgent sound of hoofbeats","Has long since faded","But the rustle of paper","Continues","Continues","Across every desk","In every study","In every civilization","That Talas touched"]}]},{"id":"chapter-14","title":"The Small Lonely Fortress","poems":[{"id":"poem-14-1","title":"The Three Hundred Warriors in Headlong Flight / Still Riding Eastward","lines":["The three hundred warriors in headlong flight","Still riding eastward","After Talas, toward the Tianshan","Toward the last outposts of the Tang","","Their commander fell at the river crossing","But they rode on","Through the dark mountains","Through the windswept passes","","Not in retreat — but in defiance","Carrying the memory of empire","In their battered armor","","Three hundred men","Against the turning tide of history","Still riding eastward","Through the endless night","","On the ridge above the valley","They paused","And looked back","At the world they were leaving behind","At the century they had owned","And lost"]},{"id":"poem-14-2","title":"The Snow Falls Like White Butterflies / Dancing on the Battlefield under the Waning Moon","lines":["The snow falls like white butterflies","Dancing on the battlefield under the waning moon","Covering the dead with a blanket","Of cold, white mercy","","By morning","The battlefield will be a white field","And no one will know","What happened here","","Until the spring thaw","Reveals the broken arrows","The rusted swords","The bones","","The snow falls like white butterflies","Beautiful and heartless","As time itself","","Drifting over Talas","Over the dead of both sides","Over the living who flee","Over the paper-maker who stays","Over the eternal, indifferent mountains"]},{"id":"poem-14-3","title":"He Must Have Heard the Waves of Issyk-Kul / Listening from Horseback","lines":["He must have heard the waves of Issyk-Kul","Listening from horseback","As the remnants crossed the western Tianshan","","The warm lake in its bowl of snow mountains","A jewel they could not stop to admire","A beauty they passed at a gallop","","He must have heard the waves","And remembered peace","And wondered if he would ever","Know peace again"]},{"id":"poem-14-4","title":"On This Path Where Silk Once Gleamed / A Young City Is About to Rise","lines":["On this path where silk once gleamed","A young city is about to rise","Not from the ruins of war","But from the stubborn human need","To build, to trade, to connect","","Where the fortress fell","A caravanserai will stand","Where soldiers bled","Merchants will bargain","","On this path where silk once gleamed","A young city is about to rise","As cities always do","On the graves of older cities","On the road that never dies"]}]},{"id":"chapter-15","title":"Emerald-Green Yarkand","poems":[{"id":"poem-15-1","title":"Carrying That Lamp / Of Holy Oil from Jerusalem","lines":["Carrying that lamp","Of holy oil from Jerusalem","The Nestorian priest walked the Silk Road eastward","Toward the kingdom of Khotan","","Christ's story traveled in his satchel","Alongside silk and spice","Faith packed between the trade goods","Light among the merchandise"]},{"id":"poem-15-2","title":"The Blue Canal of Venice / That Little City Has Faded from View","lines":["Marco Polo passed through here","Or claimed he did","The blue canal of Venice","That little city has faded from view","","Replaced by wider vistas","By deserts the Venetian had never imagined","By bazaars more magnificent","Than the markets of the Rialto","","In emerald-green Yarkand","West met East not once","But endlessly","Century after century","Merchant after merchant"]},{"id":"poem-15-3","title":"And There Is Yarkand's / Iron Cross of St. John's Church Towering High","lines":["And there is Yarkand's","Iron cross of St. John's Church towering high","Above the minarets","Above the Buddhist stupas","","Three faiths in one oasis","Three prayers rising to one sky","The Silk Road's gift:","Not uniformity, but plurality","","In Yarkand, God spoke","In every tongue that traveled the road"]},{"id":"poem-15-4","title":"Tirelessly Casting / Pale, Cold Arrows into the Desert","lines":["The moon above Yarkand","Tirelessly casting","Pale, cold arrows into the desert","","Illuminating the caravans","That still cross this ancient land","Carrying not silk now","But the memory of silk","","The memory of a road","That once connected","Every civilization on earth"]}]},{"id":"chapter-16","title":"The Silent Liupan Mountains","poems":[{"id":"poem-16-1","title":"Shooting into the Deep Forest / Shooting at the Terrified Quarry","lines":["Genghis Khan hunted in these mountains","Shooting into the deep forest","Shooting at the terrified quarry","","The greatest conqueror the world had known","Paused here, in the Liupan Mountains","Before his final campaign against the Tangut","","Death found him here","Not an enemy's arrow","But his own failing body"]},{"id":"poem-16-2","title":"Only Then Did He Mark This Circle in Red / On His Military Map","lines":["Only then did he mark this circle in red","On his military map","The Liupan Mountains","The place where the khan would die","","His generals kept the secret","Wrapped his body in felt","And carried him north","To the sacred mountain","","While the army marched on","As though the khan still led them","The greatest deception in military history","Led by a dead man on horseback"]},{"id":"poem-16-3","title":"Only in the Distant Days of Childhood / Were Nights This Quiet","lines":["Only in the distant days of childhood","Were nights this quiet","On the steppe of his birth","Before the wars, before the empire","","He remembered his mother's voice","The smell of dried horsemeat","The sound of wind in the grass","","Only in childhood","Were nights this quiet","The silence of the Liupan Mountains","Reminded him of peace","He had long forgotten"]},{"id":"poem-16-4","title":"Qiqige Filled the Carved Pot with River Water / And Walked Away","lines":["Qiqige filled the carved pot with river water","And walked away","Her Mongol braids swinging","Her bare feet on the mountain stone","","She did not know","That history was being made","On this mountainside","That the khan lay dying","In the tent above","","She only knew","The water was cold and clear","And her family was thirsty","And the pot was heavy","","History is written by generals","But carried by girls like Qiqige","Who haul water uphill","While empires rise and fall"]},{"id":"poem-16-5","title":"It Was the Song His Mother Used to Sing / Sung from the Galloping Saddle","lines":["It was the song his mother used to sing","Sung from the galloping saddle","A lullaby of the open steppe","Of eagle and deer and endless sky","","He hummed it now","In the failing light","In the Liupan Mountains","Far from the steppe of his birth","","It was the song his mother used to sing","And now it was the song","He would die to"]},{"id":"poem-16-6","title":"His Steed / Still Strikes the Earth Tirelessly under the Waning Moon","lines":["His steed","Still strikes the earth tirelessly under the waning moon","Even after the rider is gone","Even after the empire he built","Has crumbled to legend","","The horse knows no history","Only the road ahead","Only the rhythm of hooves","On ancient stone","","His steed still gallops","Through the Liupan Mountains","Through the pages of history","Through the dreams of every nomad","Who ever rode the steppe"]}]},{"id":"chapter-17","title":"The Rushing Ili River","poems":[{"id":"poem-17-1","title":"From the Upper Ili / Spring Wind Redolent with Apple Blossoms","lines":["From the upper Ili","Spring wind redolent with apple blossoms","Sweeping through the valley","Where the Dzungar people once grazed their herds","","The Ili River remembers","Every empire that drank from its waters","Wusun, Xiongnu, Turk, Mongol","All have come and gone","Like seasons"]},{"id":"poem-17-2","title":"The Blood-Red Sunset / Stains the Tears Welling in Mother's Eyes","lines":["The blood-red sunset","Stains the tears welling in mother's eyes","She watches her sons ride west","Into the Ili Valley","To reclaim a homeland lost","","The Torghut return","After a century on the Volga","Crossing the frozen steppe","Of Russia and Kazakhstan","Losing half their people to cold and war","","To come home","To the Ili Valley","To the banks of the river","That their legends never forgot"]},{"id":"poem-17-3","title":"Smiling / As Radiant as the Keziaerdake Flower","lines":["Smiling","As radiant as the Keziaerdake flower","The Kazakh girl on horseback","Rides the spring pastures of the Ili","","The war is over","The soldiers have become farmers","The blood has been washed from the grass","By a century of rain","","She rides where empires clashed","And does not know","That every flower beneath her horse's hooves","Has roots in history"]},{"id":"poem-17-4","title":"His Twenty-Two Brave Warriors Like Twenty-Two Dark Clouds / Drifting Light and Swift","lines":["His twenty-two brave warriors like twenty-two dark clouds","Drifting light and swift","Across the Ili Valley","Toward the Dzungar stronghold","","General Zhao Hui","With his small, fierce band","Changed the map of Asia","In a single summer","","The Ili, witness to so many battles","Flowed on","Carrying the reflection of dark clouds","That might have been warriors","Or might have been the sky"]},{"id":"poem-17-5","title":"Distant Mount Gegen / That Marvelous Symphony of Battle Can No Longer Be Heard","lines":["Distant Mount Gegen","That marvelous symphony of battle can no longer be heard","The stele that the emperor erected","Still stands, fading in the weather","","The inscription speaks of victory","But the mountain speaks of silence","The wind speaks of forgetting","The Ili River speaks of going on","","Distant Mount Gegen","Where war became a monument","And a monument became a stone","And a stone became part of the mountain","Indistinguishable","From the earth that holds it"]}]},{"id":"chapter-18","title":"Maimure Azimu, Fragrant as Oleaster Blossoms","poems":[{"id":"poem-18-1","title":"O, the Beautiful Tianshan Moon / Even Trampled, the Tianshan Moon Is Beautiful","lines":["O, the beautiful Tianshan moon","Even trampled, the Tianshan moon is beautiful","Shining on the face of Maimure","The Uyghur singer whose voice","Carries across the valley like silk on wind"]},{"id":"poem-18-2","title":"Slender Fingers / Caressing a Few Amber Oleaster Fruits","lines":["Slender fingers","Caressing a few amber oleaster fruits","She sings of love and loss","Of a homeland caught between empires","Her voice the only flag she needs"]},{"id":"poem-18-3","title":"The Nightingale Has Flown / Singing an Immortal Love Song","lines":["The nightingale has flown","Singing an immortal love song","That will become","The foundation of a legend:","Xiang Fei — the Fragrant Consort","Carried eastward to Beijing","Like a rare perfume","From the desert's heart"]},{"id":"poem-18-4","title":"Sapphire Eyes / Flashing Suddenly","lines":["Sapphire eyes","Flashing suddenly","In the lamplight of the imperial chamber","She remembers the oleaster groves","The moonlit nights of Kashgar","The muezzin's call at dawn","","She stands in the Forbidden City","A flower transplanted","From one garden to another","Blooming still","But yearning for the desert air"]},{"id":"poem-18-5","title":"Weaving the Prelude / To the Future Fragrant Consort's Grand Eastward March","lines":["Weaving the prelude","To the future Fragrant Consort's grand eastward march","History prepares its legends","Long before they happen","","In the oleaster groves of Kashgar","A girl sings","Not knowing she will become","The most famous woman","Of the Western Regions","","Her fragrance — real or imagined —","Will fill the halls of empire","And the pages of poetry","Forever"]}]},{"id":"chapter-19","title":"O, the Morning Star","poems":[{"id":"poem-19-1","title":"O, 1771 / This Pitch-Dark Winter Night on the Volga Steppe","lines":["O, 1771","This pitch-dark winter night on the Volga steppe","The Torghut Mongols gather in secret","Their great migration about to begin","","One hundred and seventy thousand souls","Turning east in the Russian winter","Toward a homeland most have never seen","But all have heard of in song"]},{"id":"poem-19-2","title":"Is This the Ural River? / No Rolling Waves upon Its Surface","lines":["Is this the Ural River?","No rolling waves upon its surface","Only ice, thick and treacherous","The crossing cost them dearly","","Wagons broke through","Children were lost","The old gave up and sat down in the snow","Never to rise"]},{"id":"poem-19-3","title":"Qiqige Has No More Tears / She Turns on Horseback to Gaze into the Distance","lines":["Qiqige has no more tears","She turns on horseback to gaze into the distance","The distance they have come","The distance still to go","","Half their people died on the road","Disease, starvation, Cossack raids","The Russian army pursuing","Like wolves after a weakened herd"]},{"id":"poem-19-4","title":"The Kyrgyz Steppe Still Sleeps / And the Frozen Little River","lines":["The Kyrgyz steppe still sleeps","And the frozen little river","Barely a trickle under the ice","But they press on","","Through Kazakhstan's vast emptiness","Through snow that swallows everything","Through winds that strip the skin","","The Kyrgyz steppe still sleeps","But the Torghut do not sleep","They walk through the night","Toward the morning star"]},{"id":"poem-19-5","title":"The Wooden Wheels of the Cart / Turning Slowly Eastward","lines":["The wooden wheels of the cart","Turning slowly eastward","Creaking like old bones","Like the prayer wheels of their temples","","Each revolution","One li closer to home","One li farther from exile","","The wooden wheels turn","Through snow and mud and memory","Through seven months of march","Toward the Ili Valley"]},{"id":"poem-19-6","title":"O, the Waves of Lake Balkhash / Have Long Surged in a Distant, Ethereal Dream","lines":["O, the waves of Lake Balkhash —","Have long surged in a distant, ethereal dream","And now they surge before their eyes","Blue and real and weeping with light","","They have crossed half of Eurasia","From the Volga to Lake Balkhash","Seventy thousand surviving","From one hundred and seventy thousand","","The emperor received them","At the Ili River","With ceremony and provisions","And a place to call home","","O, the morning star","That guided them through the darkest nights","Now sets in the east","Where the sun is rising","Over the Ili Valley","Over the Tianshan","Over the homeland","They had dreamed of","For a century","In exile","","The greatest migration in modern history","Written not in ink","But in blood and snow","And the turning","Of wooden wheels","Toward the morning star"]}]},{"id":"chapter-20","title":"The Frontier's Devoted Son Weeps in Anguish","poems":[{"id":"poem-20-1","title":"This Moon / Floating on the Dark-Blue Surface of Lake Balkhash","lines":["This moon","Floating on the dark-blue surface of Lake Balkhash","Is the same moon that shone on Lin Zexu","When the emperor sent him into exile","In the Western Regions","","The man who burned the opium","Who defied the British Empire","Now walks the irrigation canals of Xinjiang","A disgraced official","Doing the work of a common laborer","","But even in exile","He served","Surveying the land","Planning canals","Planting trees","","This moon witnessed","A loyal subject's punishment","And a loyal subject's unbroken spirit"]},{"id":"poem-20-2","title":"Rubbing a Page / Of the Ancient Western Regions' Historical Scroll","lines":["Rubbing a page","Of the ancient Western Regions' historical scroll","Lin Zexu traced the old canals","That Han soldiers had dug two thousand years before","","History repeating itself","Water finding its old channels","A man from the coast","Learning the language of the desert"]},{"id":"poem-20-3","title":"No Wonder the Stern Summit / Will Not Show Its Bright Face","lines":["No wonder the stern summit","Will not show its bright face","The Tianshan hides behind clouds","As if mourning the state of the empire","","Lin Zexu looked up at the mountains","And thought of the sea","Of burning ships and burning opium","Of an empire that punished him for being right","","No wonder the mountains hide","Even they are ashamed","Of what the court has become"]},{"id":"poem-20-4","title":"Beneath the Frontier Moon / A Gleaming Arrow Flies Swift","lines":["Beneath the frontier moon","A gleaming arrow flies swift","Lin Zexu's will was an arrow","Shot from exile toward justice","","He would never see Canton again","He would die on the road back from exile","An old man in a borrowed carriage","","But the canals he planned","Still carry water","In the Ili Valley","In the Tarim Basin","","Beneath the frontier moon","The gleaming arrow of his legacy","Flies on","Flies on"]}]},{"id":"chapter-21","title":"Who in the Western Regions Does Not Know Thee?","poems":[{"id":"poem-21-1","title":"Tenderly Stroking / The Ash-Brown Eagle Feather a Kazakh Herdsman Gave Him","lines":["Tenderly stroking","The ash-brown eagle feather a Kazakh herdsman gave him","The exile walks the final road","Of the Silk Road's long poem","","Two thousand years of footsteps","Footsteps and hoofbeats and wheel-tracks","All leading here, to this moment","To a man stroking an eagle feather","In the twilight of empire"]},{"id":"poem-21-2","title":"Singing Mournfully at the Frontier / The Ancient Post Road Stretching beneath His Feet","lines":["Singing mournfully at the frontier","The ancient post road stretching beneath his feet","Every stone a story","Every ruin a chapter","In the longest poem ever written","By geography and time"]},{"id":"poem-21-3","title":"Clouds Obscure the Tianshan Moon / You Softly Wipe Away Your Tears","lines":["Clouds obscure the Tianshan moon","You softly wipe away your tears","For this land that has seen","So much courage and so much sorrow","So much silk and so much blood"]},{"id":"poem-21-4","title":"Lai Lai Lai / The Loving Sayram Lake Brims with Fragrant Wine","lines":["Lai lai lai","The loving Sayram Lake brims with fragrant wine","Raise your cup to the mountains","To the road","To every traveler who has passed","Through this land of snow and fire"]},{"id":"poem-21-5","title":"He Once Loved a Blue Sea in the South / And Loves Too These Thousand Crystal Peaks of the West","lines":["He once loved a blue sea in the south","And loves too these thousand crystal peaks of the west","Two landscapes","One heart","","The south gave him warmth","The west gave him grandeur","And both gave him poetry","","Who in the Western Regions does not know thee?","After two thousand years","Of silk and tears","Of blood-sweating horses and wild poppies","Of monks and generals and princesses","Of paper-makers captured at Talas","Of envoys who would not kneel","","Who in the Western Regions does not know thee?","The Silk Road knows","The Tianshan knows","The Ili River knows","Every grain of desert sand knows"]}]}]},"children":[["$","div",null,{"className":"fixed top-4 right-4 z-50","children":["$","$L9",null,{"currentLocale":"en"}]}],["$","div",null,{"className":"max-w-4xl mx-auto pb-32","children":[["$","header",null,{"className":"pt-24 pb-12 px-8 text-center border-b border-gray-100 mb-12","children":[["$","h1",null,{"className":"text-4xl font-serif font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4","children":"Blood-Sweating Horses"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-sm text-gray-400 font-sans","children":["Li Yu"," / ","1995"]}]]}],[["$","div","chapter-1",{"className":"mb-24 px-4","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-xl font-sans font-bold text-gray-300 uppercase tracking-widest pl-8 mb-8 border-l-4 border-gray-100","children":"O, the New Continent of Central Asia"}],[["$","article",null,{"id":"poem-1-1","className":"max-w-2xl mx-auto py-32 px-8 scroll-mt-12","children":[["$","div",null,{"className":"mb-16","children":["$","h3",null,{"className":"text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 font-serif leading-relaxed","children":"That Glorious Arrow Must Still Be in Flight / Cast toward the Distant West"}]}],["$","div",null,{"className":"space-y-1 font-serif text-xl text-gray-800 leading-[2.2]","children":[["$","p","0",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"The blood-red setting sun is about to die"}],["$","p","1",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"The dark-gold curtain of night about to fall"}],["$","p","2",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":[["$","span","0",{"className":"annotation-term border-b border-dotted border-gray-400 cursor-help","title":"Zhang Qian (c. 164–114 BC) — Han Dynasty diplomat and explorer who pioneered the Silk Road route to Central Asia on behalf of Emperor Wu.","children":["Zhang Qian",["$","sup",null,{"className":"text-xs text-gray-400 ml-px select-none","children":1}]]}]," drives his herded flock homeward"]}],["$","p","3",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"A desolate pastoral song blends with the mournful reed-pipe"}],["$","p","4",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"Piercing the haze of an autumn twilight"}],["$","p","5",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"From a distant felt tent a thread of smoke rises"}],["$","p","6",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"Like a dark-gold peony from his native Hanzhong"}],["$","p","7",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"Slowly blooming across the sky of the Western Regions"}],["$","p","8",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] h-6","children":""}],["$","p","9",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"He turns to gaze at that dark-gold cloud far to the west"}],["$","p","10",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"The flock surges like waves beneath his horse"}],["$","p","11",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"O, glorious setting sun"}],["$","p","12",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"Already it has tumbled"}],["$","p","13",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"Beyond the dark-gold horizon"}],["$","p","14",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] h-6","children":""}],["$","p","15",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"Yet that glorious arrow must still be in flight"}],["$","p","16",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"Cast toward the distant west"}],["$","p","17",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"Cast toward the distant road ahead"}],["$","p","18",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"Cast toward the vast plains"}],["$","p","19",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":["Of the ",["$","span","1",{"className":"annotation-term border-b border-dotted border-gray-400 cursor-help","title":"Great Yuezhi — a nomadic people originally from the Hexi Corridor, later migrated to Central Asia. They were Zhang Qian's destination in seeking an alliance against the Xiongnu.","children":["Great Yuezhi",["$","sup",null,{"className":"text-xs text-gray-400 ml-px select-none","children":3}]]}],", longed for day and night"]}]]}],["$","div",null,{"className":"mt-16 pt-8 border-t border-gray-100","children":[["$","h4",null,{"className":"text-xs font-sans font-semibold text-gray-400 uppercase tracking-widest mb-4","children":"注释"}],["$","ol",null,{"className":"space-y-2","children":[["$","li","0",{"className":"flex text-sm text-gray-500 leading-relaxed","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"text-xs text-gray-400 mr-2 mt-0.5 flex-shrink-0 font-mono","children":[1,"."]}],["$","span",null,{"children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"font-medium text-gray-600","children":"Zhang Qian"}],["$","span",null,{"className":"mx-1.5 text-gray-300","children":"—"}],"Zhang Qian (c. 164–114 BC) — Han Dynasty diplomat and explorer who pioneered the Silk Road route to Central Asia on behalf of Emperor Wu."]}]]}],["$","li","1",{"className":"flex text-sm text-gray-500 leading-relaxed","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"text-xs text-gray-400 mr-2 mt-0.5 flex-shrink-0 font-mono","children":[2,"."]}],["$","span",null,{"children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"font-medium text-gray-600","children":"Hujia"}],["$","span",null,{"className":"mx-1.5 text-gray-300","children":"—"}],"Hujia — an ancient reed instrument of northern nomadic peoples, known for its desolate, tragic timbre, often used as a trope in frontier poetry."]}]]}],["$","li","2",{"className":"flex text-sm text-gray-500 leading-relaxed","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"text-xs text-gray-400 mr-2 mt-0.5 flex-shrink-0 font-mono","children":[3,"."]}],["$","span",null,{"children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"font-medium text-gray-600","children":"Great Yuezhi"}],["$","span",null,{"className":"mx-1.5 text-gray-300","children":"—"}],"Great Yuezhi — a nomadic people originally from the Hexi Corridor, later migrated to Central Asia. They were Zhang Qian's destination in seeking an alliance against the Xiongnu."]}]]}],["$","li","3",{"className":"flex text-sm text-gray-500 leading-relaxed","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"text-xs text-gray-400 mr-2 mt-0.5 flex-shrink-0 font-mono","children":[4,"."]}],["$","span",null,{"children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"font-medium text-gray-600","children":"Han Staff"}],["$","span",null,{"className":"mx-1.5 text-gray-300","children":"—"}],"Han Staff (jié) — the imperial envoy's staff of authority, a bamboo rod topped with yak-tail tassels symbolizing the emperor's mandate and mission."]}]]}]]}]]}],["$","div",null,{"className":"mt-20 pt-6 border-t border-gray-200","children":[["$","div",null,{"className":"flex justify-between items-center text-sm text-gray-500 font-sans","children":[["$","span",null,{"children":["《","Blood-Sweating Horses","》 · ","O, the New Continent of Central Asia"]}],"$undefined"]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"mt-2 text-xs text-gray-400 text-center","children":["Li Yu"," / ","1995"]}]]}]]}],["$","article",null,{"id":"poem-1-2","className":"max-w-2xl mx-auto py-32 px-8 scroll-mt-12","children":[["$","div",null,{"className":"mb-16","children":["$","h3",null,{"className":"text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 font-serif leading-relaxed","children":"The Clasped Hands Slowly Loosened / The Tear-Filled Eyes Abruptly Turned Away"}]}],["$","div",null,{"className":"space-y-1 font-serif text-xl text-gray-800 leading-[2.2]","children":[["$","p","0",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"The boundless steppe has fallen asleep"}],["$","p","1",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"Snow-crowned Qilian has fallen asleep"}],["$","p","2",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"The child in the felt tent must have fallen asleep too"}],["$","p","3",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] h-6","children":""}],["$","p","4",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"Standing before the black steed"}],["$","p","5",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"Gazing in silence"}],["$","p","6",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"At his weeping wife of the Western Regions"}],["$","p","7",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"Zhang Qian also weeps"}],["$","p","8",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"Tear-filled eyes meet tear-filled eyes"}],["$","p","9",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"Hands clasp hands tightly"}],["$","p","10",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] h-6","children":""}],["$","p","11",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"Her curling, tawny hair drifts in the breeze"}],["$","p","12",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"In the pale moonlight"}],["$","p","13",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"In the pale starlight"}],["$","p","14",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"Her eyes, blue as Lake Qinghai, gleam with tears"}],["$","p","15",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"Pale as the moonlight"}],["$","p","16",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"Pale as the starlight"}],["$","p","17",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] h-6","children":""}],["$","p","18",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"Her tears, ripe as grapes, fall"}],["$","p","19",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"Reflecting the pale moonlight"}],["$","p","20",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"Reflecting the pale starlight"}],["$","p","21",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] h-6","children":""}],["$","p","22",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"The black steed stamps the grass without ceasing"}],["$","p","23",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"Its sound oppressive"}],["$","p","24",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"A heavy sheepskin water-bag"}],["$","p","25",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"And a tall stack of dried naan still hang from the saddle"}],["$","p","26",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] h-6","children":""}],["$","p","27",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"Zhang Qian gazes in silence at"}],["$","p","28",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"His weeping wife"}],["$","p","29",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"Gazes in silence at"}],["$","p","30",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"The wife of the Western Regions with whom he has lived for years"}],["$","p","31",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] h-6","children":""}],["$","p","32",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"The clasped hands slowly loosen"}],["$","p","33",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"The tear-filled eyes abruptly turn away"}]]}],["$","div",null,{"className":"mt-16 pt-8 border-t border-gray-100","children":[["$","h4",null,{"className":"text-xs font-sans font-semibold text-gray-400 uppercase tracking-widest mb-4","children":"注释"}],["$","ol",null,{"className":"space-y-2","children":[["$","li","0",{"className":"flex text-sm text-gray-500 leading-relaxed","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"text-xs text-gray-400 mr-2 mt-0.5 flex-shrink-0 font-mono","children":[1,"."]}],["$","span",null,{"children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"font-medium text-gray-600","children":"Qilian Mountains"}],["$","span",null,{"className":"mx-1.5 text-gray-300","children":"—"}],"Qilian Mountains — located at the border of Gansu and Qinghai, meaning 'Heavenly Mountain' in Xiongnu. It is the southern barrier of the Hexi Corridor and an ancient crucial passage to the Western Regions."]}]]}]]}]]}],["$","div",null,{"className":"mt-20 pt-6 border-t border-gray-200","children":[["$","div",null,{"className":"flex justify-between items-center text-sm text-gray-500 font-sans","children":[["$","span",null,{"children":["《","Blood-Sweating Horses","》 · ","O, the New Continent of Central Asia"]}],"$undefined"]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"mt-2 text-xs text-gray-400 text-center","children":["Li Yu"," / ","1995"]}]]}]]}],["$","article",null,{"id":"poem-1-3","className":"max-w-2xl mx-auto py-32 px-8 scroll-mt-12","children":[["$","div",null,{"className":"mb-16","children":["$","h3",null,{"className":"text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 font-serif leading-relaxed","children":"O Great Yuezhi / The Holy Land He Has Dreamed of for Eleven Springs"}]}],["$","div",null,{"className":"space-y-1 font-serif text-xl text-gray-800 leading-[2.2]","children":[["$","p","0",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"How long he has been riding, he does not know"}],["$","p","1",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"Whether he is still riding, he is not sure"}],["$","p","2",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"In the darkness, not even the dim horizon is visible"}],["$","p","3",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"Nothing is visible"}],["$","p","4",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"All seems frozen in the profound dark"}],["$","p","5",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] h-6","children":""}],["$","p","6",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"Still he presses on with all his strength"}],["$","p","7",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":["The distance between him and ",["$","span","1",{"className":"annotation-term border-b border-dotted border-gray-400 cursor-help","title":"Tangyi Fu — Zhang Qian's loyal Xiongnu companion and guide throughout his perilous journey to the Western Regions.","children":["Tangyi Fu",["$","sup",null,{"className":"text-xs text-gray-400 ml-px select-none","children":1}]]}]," slowly narrows"]}],["$","p","8",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"But where is the mysterious Great Yuezhi?"}],["$","p","9",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"Where is the distant Great Yuezhi?"}],["$","p","10",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] h-6","children":""}],["$","p","11",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":["Just follow loyal, capable ",["$","span","1",{"className":"annotation-term border-b border-dotted border-gray-400 cursor-help","title":"Tangyi Fu — Zhang Qian's loyal Xiongnu companion and guide throughout his perilous journey to the Western Regions.","children":["Tangyi Fu",["$","sup",null,{"className":"text-xs text-gray-400 ml-px select-none","children":1}]]}]]}],["$","p","12",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"Just ride into the pitch-black west"}],["$","p","13",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"One day they shall reach their destination"}],["$","p","14",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] h-6","children":""}],["$","p","15",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"O Great Yuezhi"}],["$","p","16",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"The holy land he has dreamed of for eleven springs"}],["$","p","17",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"Through more than four thousand unbearable days in foreign lands"}],["$","p","18",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"The name he murmured ceaselessly"}],["$","p","19",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"Through more than four thousand unbearable nights in foreign lands"}],["$","p","20",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"The name he murmured ceaselessly"}],["$","p","21",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] h-6","children":""}],["$","p","22",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"From the galloping saddle he turns once more"}],["$","p","23",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"To gaze at a silhouette already lost from sight"}]]}],["$","div",null,{"className":"mt-16 pt-8 border-t border-gray-100","children":[["$","h4",null,{"className":"text-xs font-sans font-semibold text-gray-400 uppercase tracking-widest mb-4","children":"注释"}],["$","ol",null,{"className":"space-y-2","children":[["$","li","0",{"className":"flex text-sm text-gray-500 leading-relaxed","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"text-xs text-gray-400 mr-2 mt-0.5 flex-shrink-0 font-mono","children":[1,"."]}],["$","span",null,{"children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"font-medium text-gray-600","children":"Tangyi Fu"}],["$","span",null,{"className":"mx-1.5 text-gray-300","children":"—"}],"Tangyi Fu — Zhang Qian's loyal Xiongnu companion and guide throughout his perilous journey to the Western Regions."]}]]}]]}]]}],["$","div",null,{"className":"mt-20 pt-6 border-t border-gray-200","children":[["$","div",null,{"className":"flex justify-between items-center text-sm text-gray-500 font-sans","children":[["$","span",null,{"children":["《","Blood-Sweating Horses","》 · ","O, the New Continent of Central Asia"]}],"$undefined"]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"mt-2 text-xs text-gray-400 text-center","children":["Li Yu"," / ","1995"]}]]}]]}],["$","article",null,{"id":"poem-1-4","className":"max-w-2xl mx-auto py-32 px-8 scroll-mt-12","children":[["$","div",null,{"className":"mb-16","children":["$","h3",null,{"className":"text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 font-serif leading-relaxed","children":"Bathed in the Cool Radiance / That Daylight Had Yearned for Like Shade"}]}],["$","div",null,{"className":"space-y-1 font-serif text-xl text-gray-800 leading-[2.2]","children":[["$","p","0",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"That tyrannous sun —"}],["$","p","1",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"When did it sheathe its scorching golden arrows?"}],["$","p","2",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"A crescent moon above the distant western Tianshan"}],["$","p","3",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"Smiles at him tenderly"}],["$","p","4",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] h-6","children":""}],["$","p","5",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"Waking from a burning, dreadful dream"}],["$","p","6",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"He bathes in the cool, liquid light"}],["$","p","7",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"Bathes in the cool radiance"}],["$","p","8",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"That daylight had yearned for like shade"}],["$","p","9",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] h-6","children":""}],["$","p","10",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"He clenches his fist ever tighter"}],["$","p","11",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"The icy grains of sand"}],["$","p","12",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"Trickle slowly through his fingers to the ground"}],["$","p","13",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"He can hear the soft rustling sound"}],["$","p","14",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"As though the mountain stream of home flows again before him"}],["$","p","15",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"Moistening his gaunt cheeks"}],["$","p","16",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"Moistening his cracked lips"}]]}],false,["$","div",null,{"className":"mt-20 pt-6 border-t border-gray-200","children":[["$","div",null,{"className":"flex justify-between items-center text-sm text-gray-500 font-sans","children":[["$","span",null,{"children":["《","Blood-Sweating Horses","》 · ","O, the New Continent of Central Asia"]}],"$undefined"]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"mt-2 text-xs text-gray-400 text-center","children":["Li Yu"," / ","1995"]}]]}]]}],["$","article",null,{"id":"poem-1-5","className":"max-w-2xl mx-auto py-32 px-8 scroll-mt-12","children":[["$","div",null,{"className":"mb-16","children":["$","h3",null,{"className":"text-3xl font-bold text-gray-900 font-serif leading-relaxed","children":"The Pioneer of the Silk Road Smiled from Horseback / Gazing Westward"}]}],["$","div",null,{"className":"space-y-1 font-serif text-xl text-gray-800 leading-[2.2]","children":[["$","p","0",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":["No longer narrow as the ",["$","span","1",{"className":"annotation-term border-b border-dotted border-gray-400 cursor-help","title":"Hexi Corridor — a narrow passage located in northwestern Gansu between the Qilian and Beishan mountains. It was the crucial throat connecting the Central Plains to the Western Regions and a key segment of the Silk Road.","children":["Hexi Corridor",["$","sup",null,{"className":"text-xs text-gray-400 ml-px select-none","children":1}]]}]]}],["$","p","1",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"No longer a winding trail"}],["$","p","2",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"Hemmed between chains of mountains"}],["$","p","3",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] h-6","children":""}],["$","p","4",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"Gazing into the distance"}],["$","p","5",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"Slowly riding west"}],["$","p","6",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"As though on a ship of the Gobi"}],["$","p","7",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"As though listening to the distant melody of camel bells"}],["$","p","8",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"Nothing obstructs the view"}],["$","p","9",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] h-6","children":""}],["$","p","10",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"O, the new continent of Central Asia"}],["$","p","11",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"Mysterious and vast"}],["$","p","12",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"Has miraculously"}],["$","p","13",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"Appeared before the explorer bearing the Han envoy's staff"}],["$","p","14",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] h-6","children":""}],["$","p","15",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"Zhang Qian smiled"}],["$","p","16",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":["The pioneer of the ",["$","span","1",{"className":"annotation-term border-b border-dotted border-gray-400 cursor-help","title":"Silk Road — the ancient network of trade routes connecting China to Central and West Asia, and Europe, named for the Chinese silk that was heavily traded westward.","children":["Silk Road",["$","sup",null,{"className":"text-xs text-gray-400 ml-px select-none","children":2}]]}]," smiled from horseback"]}],["$","p","17",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"Gazing westward"}],["$","p","18",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"Gazing toward the still-unseen"}],["$","p","19",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"Direction of the Great Yuezhi"}],["$","p","20",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"From his cracked lips, crimson drops of blood trickled down"}],["$","p","21",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] h-6","children":""}],["$","p","22",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"April 1984"}],["$","p","23",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"(Published in *The Writer*, Issue 5, 1985)"}]]}],["$","div",null,{"className":"mt-16 pt-8 border-t border-gray-100","children":[["$","h4",null,{"className":"text-xs font-sans font-semibold text-gray-400 uppercase tracking-