) — a legendary Tang Dynasty Buddhist monk whose 17-year overland pilgrimage to India and meticulous geographic records inspired the classic novel 'Journey to the West'.","children":["Xuanzang",["$","sup",null,{"className":"text-xs text-gray-400 ml-px select-none","children":4}]]}],", the mendicant who crossed the border in secret"]}],["$","p","11",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"Now traveled with an escort fit for an emperor"}],["$","p","12",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] h-6","children":""}],["$","p","13",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"From Samarkand to Balkh"}],["$","p","14",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"From Balkh to Gandhara"}],["$","p","15",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"From Gandhara to Nalanda"}],["$","p","16",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"The greatest university the world had known"}],["$","p","17",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] h-6","children":""}],["$","p","18",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"He studied there for five years"}],["$","p","19",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"Debated the masters"}],["$","p","20",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"Translated the sutras"}],["$","p","21",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"And wept for joy"}],["$","p","22",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] h-6","children":""}],["$","p","23",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"The journey home took another seven years"}],["$","p","24",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"Through the Pamir, through Kashgar"}],["$","p","25",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"Through the very desert that had nearly killed him"}],["$","p","26",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] h-6","children":""}],["$","p","27",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"But now he carried the scriptures"}],["$","p","28",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"One thousand three hundred thirty-five volumes"}],["$","p","29",{"className":"min-h-[1.5em] ","children":"The weight of enlightenment"}],["$","p","30",{"className":"min-h-[